# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: afrikaans
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:afrikaans/a] It is similar in shape to the Ancient Greek letter alpha, from which it derives.
[src:afrikaans/a] The uppercase version consists of the two slanting sides of a triangle, crossed in the middle by a horizontal bar.
[src:afrikaans/a] The lowercase version is often written in one of two forms: the double-storey |a| and single-storey |ɑ|.
[src:afrikaans/a] The latter form is commonly used in handwriting and fonts based on it, especially fonts intended to be read by children, and is also found in italic type.
[src:afrikaans/a] In English, the name of the letter is the *long A* sound, pronounced /ˈeɪ/.
[src:afrikaans/a] Its name in most other languages matches the letter's pronunciation in open syllables.
[src:afrikaans/a] The earliest known ancestor of A is *aleph*—the first letter of the Phoenician alphabet—where it represented a glottal stop [ʔ], as Phoenician only used consonantal letters.
[src:afrikaans/a] In turn, the ancestor of aleph may have been a pictogram of an ox head in proto-Sinaitic script influenced by Egyptian hieroglyphs, styled as a triangular head with two horns extended.
[src:afrikaans/a] When the ancient Greeks adopted the alphabet, they had no use for a letter representing a glottal stop—so they adapted the sign to represent the vowel /a/, calling the letter by the similar name *alpha*.
[src:afrikaans/a] In the earliest Greek inscriptions dating to the 8th century BC following the Greek Dark Ages, the letter rests upon its side.
[src:afrikaans/a] However, in the later Greek alphabet it generally resembles the modern capital form—though many local varieties can be distinguished by the shortening of one leg, or by the angle at which the cross line is set.
[src:afrikaans/a] The Etruscans brought the Greek alphabet to the Italian Peninsula, and they left the form of alpha unchanged.
[src:afrikaans/a] When the Romans adopted the Etruscan alphabet to write Latin, the resulting form used in the Latin script would come to be used to write many other languages, including English.
[src:afrikaans/a] During Roman times, there were many variant forms of the letter A.
[src:afrikaans/a] First was the monumental or lapidary style, which was used when inscribing on stone or other more permanent media.
[src:afrikaans/a] There was also a cursive style used for everyday or utilitarian writing, which was done on more perishable surfaces.
[src:afrikaans/a] Due to the perishable nature of these surfaces, there are not as many examples of this style as there are of the monumental, but there are still many surviving examples of different types of cursive, such as majuscule cursive, minuscule cursive, and semi-cursive minuscule.
[src:afrikaans/a] Variants also existed that were intermediate between the monumental and cursive styles.
[src:afrikaans/a] The known variants include the early semi-uncial (c.
[src:afrikaans/a] 4th–8th centuries), and the late semi-uncial (c.
[src:afrikaans/a] At the end of the Roman Empire (5th century CE), several variants of the cursive minuscule developed through Western Europe.
[src:afrikaans/a] Among these were the semi-cursive minuscule of Italy, the Merovingian script in France, the Visigothic script in Spain, and the Insular or Anglo-Irish semi-uncial or Anglo-Saxon majuscule of Great Britain.
[src:afrikaans/a] By the ninth century, the Caroline script, which was very similar to the present-day form, was the principal form used in book-making, before the advent of the printing press.
[src:afrikaans/a] This form was derived through a combining of prior forms.
[src:afrikaans/a] 15th-century Italy saw the formation of the two main variants that are known today.
[src:afrikaans/a] These variants, the *Italic* and *Roman* forms, were derived from the Caroline Script version.
[src:afrikaans/a] The Italic form ⟨ɑ⟩, also called *script a*, is often used in handwriting; it consists of a circle with a vertical stroke on its right.
[src:afrikaans/a] In the hands of medieval Irish and English writers, this form gradually developed from a 5th-century form resembling the Greek letter tau ⟨τ⟩.
[src:afrikaans/a] The Roman form ⟨a⟩ is found in most printed material, and consists of a small loop with an arc over it.
[src:afrikaans/a] Both derive from the majuscule form ⟨A⟩.
[src:afrikaans/a] In Greek handwriting, it was common to join the left leg and horizontal stroke into a single loop, as demonstrated by the uncial version shown.
[src:afrikaans/a] Many fonts then made the right leg vertical.
[src:afrikaans/a] In some of these, the serif that began the right leg stroke developed into an arc, resulting in the printed form, while in others it was dropped, resulting in the modern handwritten form.
[src:afrikaans/a] Graphic designers refer to the *Italic* and *Roman* forms as *single-decker a* and *double decker a* respectively.
[src:afrikaans/a] Italic type is commonly used to mark emphasis or more generally to distinguish one part of a text from the rest set in Roman type.
[src:afrikaans/a] There are some other cases aside from italic type where *script a* ⟨ɑ⟩, also called *Latin alpha*, is used in contrast with Latin ⟨a⟩, such as in the International Phonetic Alphabet.
[src:afrikaans/a] In English, ⟨a⟩ is the indefinite article (with the alternative form *an* when followed by a vowel).
[src:afrikaans/a] The double ⟨aa⟩ sequence does not occur in native English words, but is found in some words derived from foreign languages such as *Aaron* and *aardvark*.
[src:afrikaans/a] However, ⟨a⟩ occurs in many common digraphs, all with their own sound or sounds, particularly ⟨ai⟩, ⟨au⟩, ⟨aw⟩, ⟨ay⟩, ⟨ea⟩ and ⟨oa⟩.
[src:afrikaans/a] In most languages that use the Latin alphabet, ⟨a⟩ denotes an open unrounded vowel, such as /a/, /ä/, or /ɑ/.
[src:afrikaans/a] An exception is Saanich, in which ⟨a⟩—and the glyph ⟨Á⟩—stands for a close-mid front unrounded vowel /e/.
[src:afrikaans/a] The Latin letters ⟨A⟩ and ⟨a⟩ have Unicode encodings U+0041 A LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A and U+0061 a LATIN SMALL LETTER A.
[src:afrikaans/a] These are the same code points as those used in ASCII and ISO 8859.
[src:afrikaans/a] There are also precomposed character encodings for ⟨A⟩ and ⟨a⟩ with diacritics, for most of those listed above; the remainder are produced using combining diacritics.
[src:afrikaans/a] Variant forms of the letter have unique code points for specialist use: the alphanumeric symbols set in mathematics and science, Latin alpha in linguistics, and halfwidth and fullwidth forms for legacy CJK font compatibility.
[src:afrikaans/a] The Cyrillic and Greek homoglyphs of the Latin ⟨A⟩ have separate encodings U+0410 А CYRILLIC CAPITAL LETTER A and U+0391 Α GREEK CAPITAL LETTER ALPHA.
[src:afrikaans/aardklop] The Aardklop National Arts Festival has been in existence from 1998 and has since become a bastion of arts and culture in South Africa.
[src:afrikaans/aardklop] The festival incorporates predominantly, but not exclusively, Afrikaans theatre, music, cabaret and visual arts, presented in a variety of venues across the town.
[src:afrikaans/aardklop] A large crafts market and open-air performances also form an integral part of the festival.
[src:afrikaans/aardklop] The event annually draws more than 700 artists over a period of 6 days.
[src:afrikaans/aardklop] The festival not only plays a huge role in the local economy of Potchefstroom, but also contributes largely to the economy of the greater North West Province.
[src:afrikaans/achterhooks] The Achterhooks language is spoken in the Netherlands in western Europe, Northeast, with speakers concentrated in Gelderland Province.
[src:afrikaans/achterhooks] The language was recognized by the government of the Netherlands in 1996 (as being part of Low Saxonian).
[src:afrikaans/achterhooks] The speech variety has had some growth and development, with Bible portions translated in 2002.
[src:afrikaans/affix] In linguistics, an **affix** is a morpheme that is attached to a word stem to form a new word or word form.
[src:afrikaans/affix] The two main categories are derivational and inflectional affixes.
[src:afrikaans/affix] Derivational affixes, such as *un-*, *-ation*, *anti-*, and *pre-*, introduce a semantic change to the word they are attached to.
[src:afrikaans/affix] Inflectional affixes introduce a syntactic change, such as singular into plural (e.g.
[src:afrikaans/affix] *-(e)s*), or present simple tense into present continuous or past tense by adding *-ing* or *-ed* to an English word.
[src:afrikaans/affix] All of them are bound morphemes by definition; prefixes and suffixes may be separable affixes.
[src:afrikaans/affix] Adding a morpheme at the beginning of a word is called *prefixation*, in the middle *infixation*, and at the end *suffixation*.
[src:afrikaans/affix] When marking text for interlinear glossing, as shown in the third column in the chart above, simple affixes such as prefixes and suffixes are separated from the stem with hyphens.
[src:afrikaans/affix] Affixes that disrupt the stem, or that are themselves discontinuous, are often marked off with angle brackets.
[src:afrikaans/affix] Reduplication is often shown with a tilde.
[src:afrikaans/affix] Affixes which cannot be segmented are marked with a back slash.
[src:afrikaans/affix] Semantically, lexical or semantic affixes often convey more general or abstract meanings than their corresponding free nouns.
[src:afrikaans/affix] Lexical affixes are relatively rare and are used in Wakashan, Salishan, and Chimakuan languages — the presence of these is an areal feature of the Pacific Northwest of North America - where they show little to no resemblance to free nouns with similar meanings.
[src:afrikaans/affix] Some linguists have claimed that these lexical suffixes provide only adverbial or adjectival notions to verbs.
[src:afrikaans/affix] Other linguists disagree, arguing that they may additionally be syntactic arguments just as free nouns are and, thus, equating lexical suffixes with incorporated nouns.
[src:afrikaans/affix] In sentence (1), the verb "wash" is **šak’ʷətəs** where **šak’ʷ-** is the root and **-ət** and **-əs** are inflectional suffixes.
[src:afrikaans/affix] The subject "the woman" is **łə słeniʔ** and the object "the baby" is **łə qeq**.
[src:afrikaans/affix] In this sentence, "the baby" is a free noun.
[src:afrikaans/affix] In sentence (2), "baby" does not appear as a free noun.
[src:afrikaans/affix] Instead it appears as the lexical suffix **-əyəł** which is affixed to the verb root **šk’ʷ-** (which has changed slightly in pronunciation, but this can also be ignored here).
[src:afrikaans/affix] The lexical suffix is neither "the baby" (definite) nor "a baby" (indefinite); such referential changes are routine with incorporated nouns.
[src:afrikaans/affix] In orthography, the terms for affixes may be used for the smaller elements of conjunct characters.
[src:afrikaans/affix] For example, Maya glyphs are generally compounds of a *main sign* and smaller *affixes* joined at its margins.
[src:afrikaans/affix] These are called *prefixes, superfixes, postfixes,* and *subfixes* according to their position to the left, on top, to the right, or at the bottom of the main glyph.
[src:afrikaans/affix] A small glyph placed inside another is called an *infix.* Similar terminology is found with the conjunct consonants of the Indic alphabets.
[src:afrikaans/affix] For example, the Tibetan alphabet utilizes prefix, suffix, superfix, and subfix consonant letters.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Although Afrikaans has adopted words from other languages, including German, Malay, and Khoisan languages, an estimated 90 to 95% of its vocabulary is of Dutch origin.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Differences between Afrikaans and Dutch often lie in the more analytic morphology and grammar of Afrikaans, and different spellings.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] There is a large degree of mutual intelligibility between the two languages, especially in written form.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The language's name comes directly from the Dutch word *Afrikaansch* (now spelled *Afrikaans*) meaning 'African'.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] It was previously called 'Cape Dutch' (*Kaap-Hollands* or *Kaap-Nederlands*), a term also used to refer to the early Cape settlers collectively, or the derogatory 'kitchen Dutch' (*kombuistaal*) from its use by slaves of colonial settlers "in the kitchen".
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The Afrikaans language arose in the Dutch Cape Colony through a gradual divergence from European Dutch dialects during the 18th century.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] As early as the mid-18th century and as recently as the early-20th century, many in Southern Africa viewed pre-standardized Afrikaans as 'kitchen Dutch' (Afrikaans: *kombuistaal*), lacking the prestige accorded an officially recognised language like standard Dutch and English.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] In the 19th-century Boer republics, proto-Afrikaans was not yet widely seen by the Afrikaner population or its leaders as a separate language from standard Dutch.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Dutch was expressly the sole and only legally recognised language at that time.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Other early epithets in Southern Africa setting apart *Kaaps Hollands* ('Cape Dutch', i.e.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Proto-Afrikaans) as putatively beneath official Dutch language standards included *geradbraakt*, *gebroken* and *onbeschaafd Hollands* (respectively 'mutilated', 'broken', and 'uncivilised Dutch'), as well as *verkeerd Nederlands* ('incorrect Dutch').
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Thus, in his view, Afrikaans is neither a creole nor a direct descendant of Dutch, but rather a hybrid language born from two parallel transmission pathways (a semi-creole).
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Most of the first settlers whose descendants today are the Afrikaners were from the United Provinces (now Netherlands), with up to one-sixth of the community of French Huguenot origin, and a seventh from Germany.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] African and Asian workers, Cape Coloured children of European settlers and Khoikhoi women, and slaves contributed to the development of Afrikaans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The slave population comprised people from East Africa, West Africa, Mughal India, Madagascar, and the Dutch East Indies (modern Indonesia).
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Many were also indigenous Khoisan people, who were valued as interpreters, domestic servants, and labourers.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Many free and enslaved women married or cohabited with male Dutch settlers.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Valkhoff argued that 75% of children born to female slaves in the Dutch Cape Colony between 1652 and 1672 had a Dutch father.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Beginning in about 1815, Afrikaans started to replace Malay as the language of instruction in Muslim schools in South Africa, written in Arabic Afrikaans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] These are the earliest known works written in Afrikaans, at a time when Standard Dutch was the main written language.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Later, Afrikaans, now written with the Latin script, started to appear in newspapers and political and religious works in around 1850 (alongside the already established Dutch).
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] In 1875 a group of Afrikaans-speakers from the Cape formed the *Genootskap vir Regte Afrikaaners* ('Society for Real Afrikaners'), and published a number of books in Afrikaans, including grammars, dictionaries, religious materials, and histories.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Until the early 20th century Afrikaans was considered a Dutch dialect, alongside Standard Dutch, which it eventually replaced as an official language.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Before the Boer wars, "and indeed for some time afterwards, Afrikaans was regarded as inappropriate for educated discourse.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] In 1925 Afrikaans was recognised by the South African government as a distinct language rather than simply a vernacular of Dutch.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] On 8 May 1925, 23 years after the Second Boer War ended, the Official Languages of the Union Act, 1925 was passed—mostly due to the efforts of the Afrikaans language movement—at a joint sitting of the House of Assembly and the Senate, in which the Afrikaans language was declared a variety of Dutch.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The Constitution of 1961 reversed the position of Afrikaans and Dutch, so that English and Afrikaans were the official languages and Afrikaans was deemed to include Dutch.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The Constitution of 1983 removed any mention of Dutch altogether.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The Afrikaans Language Monument is on a hill overlooking Paarl in the Western Cape Province.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Officially opened on 10 October 1975, it was erected on the 100th anniversary of the founding of the Society of Real Afrikaners, and the 50th anniversary of Afrikaans being declared an official language of South Africa in distinction to Dutch.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The earliest Afrikaans texts were some doggerel verses from 1795 and a dialogue transcribed by a Dutch traveller in 1825.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Afrikaans used the Latin alphabet around this time, although the Cape Muslim community used the Arabic script.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Meurant published his *Zamenspraak tusschen Klaas Waarzegger en Jan Twyfelaar* (*Conversation between Nicholas Truthsayer and John Doubter*), which is considered the first book published in Afrikaans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The first grammar book was published in 1876; a bilingual dictionary was published in 1902.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The main modern Afrikaans dictionary in use is the *Verklarende Handwoordeboek van die Afrikaanse Taal* (HAT).
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] A new authoritative dictionary, *Woordeboek van die Afrikaanse Taal* (WAT), was under development As of 2018.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The official orthography of Afrikaans is the *Afrikaanse Woordelys en Spelreëls*, compiled by *Die Taalkommissie*.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The Afrikaners primarily were Protestants, of the Dutch Reformed Church of the 17th century.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Their religious practices were later influenced in South Africa by British ministries during the 1800s.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] A landmark in the language's development was the translation of the Bible into Afrikaans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] While significant advances had been made in the textual criticism of the Bible, especially the Greek New Testament, the 1933 translation followed the Textus Receptus and was closely akin to the *Statenbijbel*.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Before this, most Cape Dutch-Afrikaans speakers had to rely on the Dutch *Statenbijbel*.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] This *Statenvertaling* had its origins with the Synod of Dordrecht of 1618 and was thus in an archaic form of Dutch.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] This was hard for Dutch speakers to understand, and increasingly unintelligible for Afrikaans speakers.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Hoogehout, Arnoldus Pannevis, and Stephanus Jacobus du Toit were the first Afrikaans Bible translators.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] An important landmark in the translation of the Scriptures as C.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Hoogehout's 1878 translation of the *Evangelie volgens Markus* (Gospel of Mark, lit.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] 'Gospel according to Mark'), but it was never published.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The manuscript is in the South African National Library, Cape Town.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The first official translation of the entire Bible into Afrikaans was in 1933 by J.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] In 1983 a fresh translation marked the 50th anniversary of the 1933 version.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] It was influenced by Eugene Nida's theory of dynamic equivalence, which focused on finding the nearest equivalent in the receptor language to the idea that the Greek, Hebrew, or Aramaic conveyed.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] A new translation, *Die Bybel: 'n Direkte Vertaling* was released in November 2020.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] It is the first truly ecumenical translation of the Bible in Afrikaans as translators from various churches, including the Roman Catholic and Anglican Churches, were involved.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Afrikaans descended from Dutch dialects in the 17th century.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] It belongs to a West Germanic sub-group, the Low Franconian languages.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Other West Germanic languages related to Afrikaans are German, English, the Frisian languages, Yiddish, and the unstandardised language Low German.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Besides South-Africa, Afrikaans is also widely spoken in Namibia.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Before independence, Afrikaans had equal status with German as an official language.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Since independence in 1990, Afrikaans has had constitutional recognition as a national, but not official, language.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] There is a much smaller number of Afrikaans speakers among Zimbabwe's white minority, as most have left the country since 1980.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Afrikaans was also a medium of instruction for schools in Bophuthatswana, an Apartheid-era Bantustan.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Eldoret, Kenya, was founded by Afrikaners.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] There are also around 30,000 South Africans in the Netherlands, of which the majority are of Afrikaans-speaking Afrikaner and Coloured South-African descent.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] A much smaller and unknown number of Afrikaans speakers also reside in the Dutch Caribbean.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Contrary to popular belief, the majority of Afrikaans speakers today are not Afrikaners or Boers, but Coloureds.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] In 1976, secondary-school pupils in Soweto began a rebellion in response to the government's decision that Afrikaans be used as the language of instruction for half the subjects taught in non-White schools (with English continuing for the other half).
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Although English is the mother tongue of only 8.2% of the population, it is the language most widely understood, and the second language of a majority of South Africans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Afrikaans is more widely spoken than English in the Northern and Western Cape provinces, several hundred kilometres from Soweto.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The Black community's opposition to Afrikaans and preference for continuing English instruction was underlined when the government rescinded the policy one month after the uprising: 96% of Black schools chose English (over Afrikaans or native languages) as the language of instruction.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Afrikaans-medium schools were also accused of using language policy to deter Black African parents.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Some of these parents, in part supported by provincial departments of education, initiated litigation which enabled enrolment with English as language of instruction.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] By 2006 there were 300 single-medium Afrikaans schools, compared to 2,500 in 1994, after most converted to dual-medium education.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Due to Afrikaans being viewed as the "language of the white oppressor" by some, pressure has been increased to remove Afrikaans as a teaching language in South African universities, resulting in bloody student protests in 2015.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Under South Africa's Constitution of 1996, Afrikaans remains an official language, and has equal status to English and ten other languages.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The new policy means that the use of Afrikaans is now often reduced in favour of English, or to accommodate the other official languages.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] In 1996, for example, the South African Broadcasting Corporation reduced the amount of television airtime in Afrikaans, while South African Airways dropped its Afrikaans name *Suid-Afrikaanse Lugdiens* from its livery.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Similarly, South Africa's diplomatic missions overseas now display the name of the country only in English and their host country's language, and not in Afrikaans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Meanwhile, the constitution of the Western Cape, which went into effect in 1998, declares Afrikaans to be an official language of the province alongside English and Xhosa.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The Afrikaans-language general-interest family magazine *Huisgenoot* has the largest readership of any magazine in the country.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The author of the article, Bronwyn Davies, was an English-speaking South African.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] An estimated 90 to 95 percent of the Afrikaans lexicon is ultimately of Dutch origin, and there are few lexical differences between the two languages.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Afrikaans has a considerably more regular morphology, grammar, and spelling.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] There is a high degree of mutual intelligibility between the two languages, particularly in written form.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Afrikaans acquired some lexical and syntactical borrowings from other languages such as Malay, Khoisan languages, Portuguese, German and Bantu languages.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Afrikaans has also been significantly influenced by South African English, especially in the Western Cape.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Dutch speakers are confronted with fewer non-cognates when listening to Afrikaans than the other way round.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Mutual intelligibility thus tends to be asymmetrical, as it is easier for Dutch speakers to understand Afrikaans than for Afrikaans speakers to understand Dutch.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] In general, mutual intelligibility between Dutch and Afrikaans is far better than between Dutch and Frisian or between Danish and Swedish.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The South African poet writer Breyten Breytenbach, attempting to visualise the language distance for Anglophones, once remarked that the differences between (Standard) Dutch and Afrikaans are comparable to those between the Received Pronunciation and Southern American English.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Afrikaans is an official language of the Republic of South Africa and a recognised national language of the Republic of Namibia.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Post-apartheid South Africa has seen a loss of preferential treatment by the government for Afrikaans, in terms of education, social events, media (TV and radio), and general status throughout the country, given that it now shares its place as official language with ten other languages.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Nevertheless, Afrikaans remains more prevalent in the media – radio, newspapers and television – than any of the other official languages except English.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] More than 300 book titles in Afrikaans are published annually.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] South African census figures suggest a decreasing number of first language Afrikaans speakers in South Africa from 13.5% in 2011 to 10.6% in 2022.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The South African Institute of Race Relations (SAIRR) projects that a growing majority of Afrikaans speakers will be Coloured.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Afrikaans speakers experience higher employment rates than other South African language groups, though as of 2012 half a million were unemployed.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Despite the challenges of demotion and emigration that it faces in South Africa, the Afrikaans vernacular remains competitive, being popular in DSTV pay channels and several internet sites, while generating high newspaper and music CD sales.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] A resurgence in Afrikaans popular music since the late 1990s has invigorated the language, especially among a younger generation of South Africans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] A recent trend is the increased availability of pre-school educational CDs and DVDs.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Such media also prove popular with the extensive Afrikaans-speaking emigrant communities who seek to retain language proficiency in a household context.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Afrikaans-language cinema showed signs of new vigour in the early 21st century.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The 2007 film *Ouma se slim kind*, the first full-length Afrikaans movie since *Paljas* in 1998, is seen as the dawn of a new era in Afrikaans cinema.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Several short films have been created and more feature-length movies, such as *Poena Is Koning* and *Bakgat* (both in 2008) have been produced, besides the 2011 Afrikaans-language film *Skoonheid*, which was the first Afrikaans film to screen at the Cannes Film Festival.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The film *Platteland* was also released in 2011.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The Afrikaans film industry started gaining international recognition via the likes of big Afrikaans Hollywood film stars, like Charlize Theron (*Monster*) and Sharlto Copley (*District 9*) promoting their mother tongue.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] SABC 3 announced early in 2009 that it would increase Afrikaans programming due to the "growing Afrikaans-language market and [their] need for working capital as Afrikaans advertising is the only advertising that sells in the current South African television market".
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] In April 2009, SABC3 started screening several Afrikaans-language programmes.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] There is a groundswell movement within Afrikaans to be inclusive, and to promote itself along with the indigenous official languages.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] In Namibia, the percentage of Afrikaans speakers declined from 11.4% (2001 Census) to 10.4% (2011 Census).
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Some native speakers of Bantu languages and English also speak Afrikaans as a second language.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] It is widely taught in South African schools, with about 10.3 million second-language students.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Afrikaans is offered at many universities outside South Africa, including in the Netherlands, Belgium, Germany, Poland, Russia and the United States.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] In Afrikaans grammar, there is no distinction between the infinitive and present forms of verbs, with the exception of the verbs 'to be' and 'to have'.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] In addition, verbs do not conjugate differently depending on the subject.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Only a handful of Afrikaans verbs have a preterite, namely the auxiliary *wees* ('to be'), the modal verbs, and the verb *dink* ('to think').
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The preterite of *mag* ('may') is rare in contemporary Afrikaans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] All other verbs use the perfect tense, het + past participle (ge-), for the past.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Therefore, there is no distinction in Afrikaans between *I drank* and *I have drunk*.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] When telling a longer story, Afrikaans speakers usually avoid the perfect and simply use the present tense, or historical present tense instead (as is possible, but less common, in English as well).
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] A particular feature of Afrikaans is its use of the double negative; it is classified in Afrikaans as **ontkennende vorm** and is something that is absent from the other West Germanic standard languages.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Both French and San origins have been suggested for double negation in Afrikaans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] While double negation is still found in Low Franconian dialects in West Flanders and in some "isolated" villages in the centre of the Netherlands (such as Garderen), it takes a different form, which is not found in Afrikaans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The *-ne* was the Middle Dutch way to negate but it has been suggested that since *-ne* became highly non-voiced, *nie* or *niet* was needed to complement the *-ne*.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] With time the *-ne* disappeared in most Dutch dialects.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] A notable exception to this is the use of the negating grammar form that coincides with negating the English present participle.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] In this case there is only a single negation.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Hy is in die hospitaal, maar hy eet nie.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Hij is in het ziekenhuis, maar hij eet niet.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] English: He is in [the] hospital, though he doesn't eat.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Certain words in Afrikaans would be contracted.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] For example, *moet nie*, which literally means 'must not', usually becomes *moenie*; although one does not have to write or say it like this, virtually all Afrikaans speakers will change the two words to *moenie* in the same way as *do not* is contracted to *don't* in English.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The Dutch word *het* ('it' in English) does not correspond to *het* in Afrikaans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The Dutch words corresponding to Afrikaans *het* are *heb*, *hebt*, *heeft* and *hebben*.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Following early dialectal studies of Afrikaans, it was theorised that three main historical dialects probably existed after the Great Trek in the 1830s.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] These dialects are the Northern Cape, Western Cape, and Eastern Cape dialects.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Northern Cape dialect may have resulted from contact between Dutch settlers and the Khoekhoe people between the Great Karoo and the Kunene, and Eastern Cape dialect between the Dutch and the Xhosa.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Remnants of these dialects still remain in present-day Afrikaans, although the standardising effect of Standard Afrikaans has contributed to a great levelling of differences in modern times.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Oranjerivier-Afrikaans (Orange River Afrikaans) is a major variety, including the Oranjerivier Afrikaans spoken by whites and Griqua Afrikaans spoken by Griqua as well as Namakwalands.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] There is also a prison cant, known as Sabela, which is based on Afrikaans, yet heavily influenced by Zulu.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] This language is used as a secret language in prison and is taught to initiates.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Patagonian Afrikaans is a distinct dialect of Afrikaans that is spoken by the 650-member South African community of Argentina, in the region of Patagonia.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Namibian Afrikaans is a variety of Afrikaans spoken in Namibia.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The country was governed by South Africa until 1990, which had favoured Afrikaans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Before that, Dutch had been introduced when the Dutch occupied Walvis Bay and the surrounding area.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Due to the early settlement of a Cape Malay community in Cape Town, who are now known as Coloureds, numerous Classical Malay words were brought into Afrikaans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Some of these words entered Dutch via people arriving from what is now known as Indonesia as part of their colonial heritage.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Some words originally came from Portuguese such as *sambreel* ('umbrella') from the Portuguese *sombreiro*, *kraal* ('pen/cattle enclosure') from the Portuguese *curral* and *mielie* ('corn', from *milho*).
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Some of these words also exist in Dutch, like *sambreel* 'parasol', though usage is less common and meanings can slightly differ.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Some of these words also exist in Dutch, though with a more specific meaning: *assegaai* for example means 'South-African tribal javelin' and *karos* means 'South-African tribal blanket of animal hides'.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Loanwords from Bantu languages in Afrikaans include the names of indigenous birds, such as *mahem* and *sakaboela*, and indigenous plants, such as *maroela* and *tamboekie(gras)*.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The revoking of the Edict of Nantes on 22 October 1685 was a milestone in the history of South Africa, for it marked the beginning of the great Huguenot exodus from France.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] It is estimated that between 250,000 and 300,000 Protestants left France between 1685 and 1700; out of these, according to Louvois, 100,000 had received military training.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] A measure of the calibre of these immigrants and of their acceptance by host countries (in particular South Africa) is given by H.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Morton in his book: *In Search of South Africa* (London, 1948).
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The Huguenots were responsible for a great linguistic contribution to Afrikaans, particularly in terms of military terminology as many of them fought on the battlefields during the wars of the Great Trek.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Most of the words in this list are descendants from Dutch borrowings from French, Old French or Latin, and are not direct influences from French on Afrikaans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The Afrikaans writing system is based on Dutch, using the 26 letters of the ISO basic Latin alphabet, plus 16 additional vowel sounds represented by adding diacritics.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The hyphen (e.g. in a compound like *see-eend* 'sea duck'), apostrophe (e.g.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] *ma's* 'mothers'), and a whitespace character (e.g. in multi-word units like *Dooie See* 'Dead Sea') is part of the orthography of words, while the indefinite article *ŉ* is a ligature.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] All the alphabet letters, including those with diacritics, have capital letters as allographs; the *ŉ* does not have a capital letter allograph.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] This means that Afrikaans has 88 graphemes with allographs in total.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] In Afrikaans, many consonants are dropped from the earlier Dutch spelling.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] For example, **slechts** ('only') in Dutch becomes **slegs** in Afrikaans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Also, Afrikaans and some Dutch dialects make no distinction between /s/ and /z/, having merged the latter into the former; while the word for "south" is written **zuid** in Dutch, it is spelled **suid** in Afrikaans (as well as dialectal Dutch writings) to represent this merger.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Similarly, the Dutch digraph **ĳ**, normally pronounced as /ɛi/, corresponds to Afrikaans **y**, except where it replaces the Dutch suffix **–lijk** which is pronounced as /lək/, as in **waarschijnlijk* > *waarskynlik**.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Another difference is the indefinite article, **'n** in Afrikaans and *een* in Dutch.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] "A book" is **'n boek** in Afrikaans, whereas it is either **een boek** or **'n boek** in Dutch.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] This **'n** is usually pronounced as just a weak vowel, [ə], just like English "a".
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The diminutive suffix in Afrikaans is **-tjie**, **-djie** or **-ie**, whereas in Dutch it is **-tje** or **dje**, hence a "bit" is ŉ *bie**tjie*** in Afrikaans and *bee**tje*** in Dutch.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The letters *c*, *q*, *x*, and *z* occur almost exclusively in borrowings from French, English, Greek and Latin.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] This is usually because words that had *c* and *ch* in the original Dutch are spelled with *k* and *g*, respectively, in Afrikaans.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Similarly original *qu* and *x* are most often spelt *kw* and *ks*, respectively.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] For example, **ekwatoriaal** instead of *equatoriaal*, and **ekskuus** instead of *excuus*.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Diacritics are ignored when alphabetising, but it is important to include them even if they are difficult to type.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] For example, **geëet** ("ate") instead of the 3 e's alongside each other: ***geeet**, which can never occur in Afrikaans, or **sê**, which translates to "say", whereas **se** is a possessive form.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The primary function of the acute accent (*á*, *é*, *í*, *ó*, *ú, ý)* is to indicate an emphasised syllable.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The acute is only placed on an *i* if that is the only vowel in an emphasised word: *wil* ('want' (verb)) becomes *wíl*, but *lui* ('lazy') becomes *lúi.* Only a few non-loan words are spelled with acutes, e.g.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] A few short words in Afrikaans take initial apostrophes.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] In modern Afrikaans, these words are always written in lower case (except when writing in all-capitals); if they occur at the beginning of a sentence, the following word that has no initial apostrophe is capitalised instead.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Three examples of such apostrophed words are **'k, 't, 'n**.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The last (the indefinite article) is the only such word common in modern written Afrikaans, since the others are shortened versions of words that are usually written out (**ek** and **het**, respectively) and are rarely found outside of a poetic context.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] The apostrophe and the following letter are regarded as two separate characters, and are never written using a single glyph, although a single-character variant of the indefinite article appears in Unicode, *ŉ*.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] For more on the pronunciation of the letters below, see *Help:IPA/Afrikaans*.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Alle menslike wesens word vry, met gelyke waardigheid en regte, gebore.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Hulle het rede en gewete en behoort in die gees van broederskap teenoor mekaar op te tree.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Die Here is my Herder, niks sal my ontbreek nie.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Hy laat my neerlê in groen weivelde; na waters waar rus is, lei Hy my heen.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Hy verkwik my siel; Hy lei my in die spore van geregtigheid, om sy Naam ontwil.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Al gaan ek ook in 'n dal van doodskaduwee, ek sal geen onheil vrees nie; want U is met my: u stok en u staf die vertroos my.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Die Here is my Herder, ek kom niks kort nie.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Hy bring my by waters waar daar vrede is.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Hy lei my op die regte paaie tot eer van Sy naam.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Selfs al gaan ek deur donker dieptes, sal ek nie bang wees nie, want U is by my.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Ons Vader in die hemel, laat u Naam geheilig word.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Laat u wil hier op aarde uitgevoer word soos in die hemel.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Gee ons die porsie brood wat ons vir vandag nodig het.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] En vergeef ons ons sondeskuld soos ons ook óns skuldenaars vergewe het.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Bewaar ons sodat ons nie aan verleiding sal toegee nie; maar bevry ons van die greep van die bose.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Want aan U behoort die koningskap, en die krag, en die heerlikheid, vir altyd.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Onse Vader wat in die hemel is, laat U Naam geheilig word; laat U koninkryk kom; laat U wil geskied op die aarde, net soos in die hemel.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-eastern-cape-dialect] Gee ons vandag ons daaglikse brood; en vergeef ons ons skulde soos ons ons skuldenaars vergewe en laat ons nie in die versoeking nie maar verlos ons van die bose Want aan U behoort die koninkryk en die krag en die heerlikheid tot in ewigheid.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-language-monument] The **Afrikaans Language Monument** (Afrikaans: *Afrikaanse Taalmonument*) is located on a hill overlooking Paarl, Western Cape Province, South Africa.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-language-monument] Officially opened on 10 October 1975, it commemorates the semicentenary of Afrikaans being declared an official language of South Africa separate from Dutch.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-language-monument] In addition, it was erected on the 100th anniversary of the founding of Genootskap van Regte Afrikaners (the Society of Real Afrikaners) in Paarl, the organisation that helped strengthen Afrikaners' identity and pride in their language.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-language-monument] There is also an open stadium at the bottom of the structure where concerts and events are held.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-language-monument] The phrase *"DIT IS ONS ERNS"* (roughly "we are earnest [about this]", or "this is our earnestness") is emblazoned on the pathway leading up to the monument.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-language-monument] The first monument to commemorate Afrikaans was the monument in Burgersdorp, which was built in 1893, although it refers to the *Hollandse taal* or *the Dutch language*.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-language-monument] It depicts a woman pointing her finger at a book in her hands.
[src:afrikaans/afrikaans-language-monument] Afrikaans Language Monument was created out of stones stacked by visitors at Petrus Steyn, Free State, on 14 August 1975, in celebration of the centenary of the Afrikaans Language.
